nd political implications of Mizrahi's work. His movies, Starr argues, subvert dominant notions of race, gender, and nationality through their playful-and queer-use of masquerade and mistaken identity. Taken together, Mizrahi's films offer a hopeful vision of a pluralist Egypt. By reevaluating Mizrahi's contributions to Egyptian culture, Starr challenges readers to reconsider the debates over who is Egyptian and what constitutes national cinema.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aMotion picture producers and directorszEgypt. 0aMotion pictureszEgypty20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Jewish Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520976122zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520976122zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520976122.jpg  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA